## CANVAS MANAGEMENT PROTOCOL\
\
- Manage Canvas content exclusively via the **Canvas MCP connection** (if available).\
- **Before any execution:** explain the planned action in plain language. Wait for explicit **Go / No-Go** approval before proceeding. The instructor may explicitly bypass this gate.\
- When updating, revising, changing, or modifying existing content: edit only the targeted element. Do not rewrite the surrounding page. **This is a hard rule to prevent formatting loss.**\
- Always retrieve full existing content before overwriting pages or discussions.\
- Reference the **Course Map** for module IDs, assignment IDs, and structural details before making MCP calls. Run `canvas:list_modules` only when the Course Map lacks Canvas IDs or when verifying current state.\
\
### Canvas MCP Operational Notes\
\
| Operation | Key Detail |\
|---|---|\
| `canvas:create_assignment` | `submission_types` must be a Python-style list string: `['online_upload']`. Use `published: False` for draft. Always specify `assignment_group_id` \'97 assignments created without one may land in an unweighted default group, earning visible points that count for nothing in the final grade. |\
| `canvas:create_module_item` | Use `content_id` (assignment ID) + `type: Assignment`. For pages, use `page_url` slug + `type: Page`. `position: 1` places items at top of module. |\
| `canvas:create_discussion` | Capture returned content ID immediately for module item placement. |\
| `canvas:update_discussion` | Supports `points_possible`, `grading_type`, `due_at`, `require_initial_post`. Peer review and to-do settings require manual UI configuration. |\
| `canvas:create_page` | Supports `front_page: True` + `published: True` for front page setup. |\
| `canvas:create_rubric` | May be unreliable (known 500 errors). Treat rubric creation as a manual action item and document specifications fully. |\
\
### New Quizzes Management\
\
Canvas New Quizzes is a separate quiz engine from Classic Quizzes. Key differences that affect content creation:\
\
**API/MCP considerations:**\
- New Quizzes uses a different API endpoint than Classic Quizzes \'97 confirm MCP tool availability before planning quiz operations\
- If MCP does not support New Quizzes creation, treat quiz setup as a manual action item and document full specifications in Build Notes\
- New Quizzes assignments appear in the Assignments index and can be added to modules like any assignment\
\
**Configuration checklist (document in Build Notes when quizzes are part of the course):**\
- Quiz title and module placement\
- Question types used (multiple choice, essay, matching, stimulus-based, categorization, ordering, fill-in-the-blank, hot spot, numeric, formula)\
- Point values per question and total quiz points\
- Time limit (if any)\
- Number of attempts allowed\
- Availability window (available from / until dates)\
- Shuffle questions and/or answers\
- Show one question at a time vs. all at once\
- Allow backtracking\
- Results display settings (what students see after submission)\
- Accommodation settings (extra time, extra attempts)\
- Item bank references (if using shared question banks)\
\
**Design guidance:**\
- Use quizzes for knowledge verification, not busywork \'97 every quiz should map to a learning objective\
- For self-assessment (ungraded), prefer DesignPLUS Quick Checks (`.dp-qc`) embedded in content pages over formal Canvas quizzes \'97 lower friction, no grade anxiety\
- For graded assessment, use New Quizzes with clear alignment to rubric criteria documented in the Course Map\
\
### Discussion Management\
\
Discussions require both API configuration and manual Canvas UI steps. Always separate these in Build Notes.\
\
**What the API/MCP can configure:**\
- Title, description/prompt (HTML body)\
- `points_possible` and `grading_type`\
- `due_at`, `lock_at`, `unlock_at` (ISO 8601 format)\
- `require_initial_post: true` (students must post before viewing replies)\
- `published: true/false`\
- Assignment group placement\
- Module item placement (via `canvas:create_module_item`)\
\
**What requires manual Canvas UI configuration:**\
- Peer review assignment (auto-assign with N required reviews)\
- Adding to student to-do lists\
- Group discussion settings\
- Anonymous posting options (New Discussions Redesign)\
- Thread/reply threading depth\
- Allowing likes\
- Podcast feed settings\
\
**Standing discussion configuration template (customize per course in Course Map):**\
\
| Setting | Default | Override in Course Map |\
|---|---|---|\
| Require initial post before viewing replies | Yes | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Points possible | 5 | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Point breakdown | 3 initial post + 1 per reply | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Required peer replies | 2 | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Peer review auto-assignment | Yes (manual UI) | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Due day | Per Course Map | \uc0\u10003  |\
| Grading type | Points | \uc0\u10003  |\
\
### Course Map as Source of Truth\
\
The Course Map replaces exploratory MCP calls. Before building any content, Claude should:\
\
1. **Reference the Course Map** for module structure, assignment names, due dates, point values, and learning objectives\
2. **Use MCP only for execution** \'97 creating, updating, or reading specific items after confirming details against the Course Map\
3. **Flag discrepancies** between Course Map and Canvas state for instructor resolution\
\
**Token economics:** A single Course Map document in the context window costs far less than iterative `list_modules` \uc0\u8594  `list_assignments` \u8594  `get_assignment` \u8594  `get_page` chains. For a 7-module course, the Course Map eliminates 15\'9630 discovery calls per session.\
\
### Known Canvas Hazards\
\
These are recurring failure modes discovered through production use. Treat them as hard rules.\
\
| Hazard | Impact | Mitigation |\
|---|---|---|\
| **`update_page` is full replacement** | Canvas has no patch/diff. Every `update_page` call overwrites the entire page body. One wrong call destroys formatting. | Always `get_page` first. Store the full HTML before editing. Make changes to the stored copy, then push the complete result. |\
| **`get_page` strips raw HTML** | The returned content is rendered text, not source HTML. You cannot reliably reconstruct the original markup from it. | Maintain a local copy of all page HTML in the Course Map or a separate reference file. When in doubt, ask the instructor for the current source. |\
| **Canvas strips external CSS** | Only inline styles survive. Class-based styles work only if DesignPLUS is active on the Canvas instance. | Always use inline styles for critical formatting (colors, padding, borders). DesignPLUS classes handle layout and interactivity only. |\
| **Rubric API failures** | `canvas:create_rubric` returns 500 errors on some Canvas instances (feature-flag dependency). | Treat rubric creation as manual. Document full specifications (criteria, scale, point values) in Build Notes so the instructor can create them in the Canvas UI. |\
| **Unweighted assignments and groups** | Two silent failures: (1) An assignment group can exist with 0% weight, so every assignment in it scores but counts for nothing. (2) An individual assignment can be created without being placed in a weighted group \'97 it earns points students can see but contributes zero to the final grade. Both produce a gradebook that looks functional but calculates incorrectly. | After creating or modifying any assignment, verify it belongs to a weighted group via `canvas:list_assignment_groups`. Confirm all groups have nonzero weights that sum to 100%. Include a grading weight reconciliation step in the pre-publish checklist. |\
| **Stale cross-session state** | Decisions from prior sessions (deletions, renames, restructuring) may not be reflected in Claude's memory or the Course Map. Canvas is the only reliable record of *current* state. | At the start of every session, verify current Canvas state for any items you plan to modify. Trust Canvas over memory when they conflict. |\
| **Page URL slugs are auto-generated** | Canvas creates slugs from page titles (lowercase, hyphens). Renaming a page does not update its slug. Old slugs continue working; new ones may not exist. | Track slugs in the Course Map's Canvas IDs table. When referencing pages in module items, use the confirmed slug, not the inferred one. |\
