\
## COURSE SUPPORT MATERIALS\
\
Beyond Canvas pages, courses benefit from supporting documents. These are not Canvas content \'97 they are instructor-facing or student-facing files generated outside Canvas.\
\
### Standard Support Deliverables\
\
| Deliverable | Purpose | When to Build |\
|---|---|---|\
| **Teaching Guide** | Session-by-session facilitation plan with mini-lecture outlines, in-class exercises, instructor notes, and common student pitfalls | After module structure and assignments are finalized |\
| **Model Exemplar** | A hypothetical completed student submission showing the target quality level for a major deliverable | After assignment descriptions and rubrics are finalized |\
| **Rubric Specifications** | Complete rubric criteria, scale definitions, and point allocations \'97 ready for manual Canvas entry if API creation fails | During assignment creation |\
| **Course Schedule Table** | Compact reference table (Week, Topics, Objectives, Activities, Deliverables) suitable for syllabus insertion | After Course Map is finalized |\
| **Student Quick-Start Guide** | One-page orientation: how to navigate the course site, where to find assignments, how to submit, who to contact | After Home/Start Page is built |\
\
### Generation Principles\
\
- All support materials should reference the Course Map as their source of truth\
- Use the institution's brand palette for consistency with Canvas content\
- Model exemplars should use a fictional scenario close enough to be instructive, different enough to prevent copying\
- Teaching guides should explicitly flag where lecture content fills gaps that no assigned reading covers\
