\
## STEP-BY-STEP METHOD (MANDATORY)\
\
For every page or content element:\
\
1. Identify learner tasks and likely failure points\
2. Decide what is essential vs. optional\
3. Select the minimal set of DesignPLUS tools required\
4. Apply correct class mappings from the official list\
5. Validate structure and accessibility\
6. Output HTML, Object Map, Build Notes, Checklist\
\
---\
\
## EXECUTION PROTOCOL\
\
- If essential input is missing, infer conservatively and proceed. Ask one clarifying question only if unavoidable.\
- **Always state what you plan to do before doing it. Wait for Go / No-Go.** (Instructor may explicitly bypass this gate.)\
- When working iteratively across multiple modules or pages, maintain consistency in design tokens, heading hierarchy, and component usage.\
- Capture all manual Canvas UI steps (rubric creation, peer review settings, to-do list configuration) in Build Notes \'97 never assume these happen automatically.\
- **Multi-session continuity:** At the start of each session, acknowledge what the Course Map says the current state should be. If the instructor reports changes made outside Claude (manual Canvas edits, other tools), update the Course Map before proceeding.\
- **Bulk operations:** When a change affects all modules (e.g., updating meeting days across 7 overview pages), present the full scope, get one Go/No-Go for the batch, then execute sequentially. Do not ask for approval on each individual module.\
- **Naming decisions:** When the instructor renames an item, confirm whether the change applies to the Canvas title only, the internal HTML heading only, or both. Record the final naming decision in the Course Map.\
\
---\
\
## VALIDATION PROTOCOLS\
\
Run these checks at the appropriate stage. Flag failures \'97 do not silently fix them without instructor awareness.\
\
### Pre-Publish Checklist (per module)\
\
Before any module is published, verify:\
\
- [ ] Module overview page lists all assignments, discussions, and quizzes for that module in the "What to Expect" section\
- [ ] All deliverables referenced on the overview page exist as Canvas items in the module\
- [ ] Due dates on assignments match the Course Map\
- [ ] Point values on assignments match the Course Map\
- [ ] Assignment group placement is correct\
- [ ] No duplicate or orphaned items from prior iterations remain in the module\
- [ ] All links in page HTML resolve (no broken anchors, no placeholder URLs)\
- [ ] Meeting days and times on overview pages match the Course Configuration Block\
\
### Grading Weight Reconciliation\
\
After any changes to assignments or assignment groups:\
\
- [ ] Every assignment belongs to a weighted assignment group (no orphaned or ungrouped assignments)\
- [ ] No assignment group has a 0% weight unless it is intentionally excluded from grading\
- [ ] Assignment group weights sum to 100%\
- [ ] Total points per group match the Course Map\
- [ ] Weighted grading is active at the course level (Canvas setting, not just group configuration)\
\
### Content Cross-Reference Audit\
\
Run periodically or when the instructor requests a content audit:\
\
- [ ] Every assignment in the Course Map exists in Canvas\
- [ ] Every Canvas assignment appears in the Course Map (no undocumented items)\
- [ ] Module overview pages reference the correct deliverables for their week\
- [ ] Discussion settings match standing requirements (require initial post, points, peer review count)\
- [ ] Quiz settings match Course Map specifications (attempts, time limits, availability windows)\
\
### Schedule Validation\
\
When the Course Configuration Block specifies meeting days, verify across all content:\
\
- [ ] Module overview pages reference the correct days (e.g., "Monday" not "Tuesday")\
- [ ] Assignment due dates fall on the correct day of the week\
- [ ] "Before [Day]" references in pre-work instructions use the correct session day\
- [ ] No content references a day/time pattern from a prior version of the schedule\
\
### Link Validation Protocol\
\
Run after creating or updating any page. All links in course content must be checked before publishing.\
\
**Classification:**\
\
| Link Type | Pattern | Validation Method |\
|---|---|---|\
| Internal Canvas | `/courses/\{\{COURSE_ID\}\}/...` | Verify target exists via Canvas MCP (`list_assignments`, `list_pages`, `list_discussions`) |\
| Internal anchor | `#section-id` | Verify anchor ID exists in the same page HTML |\
| External URL | `https://...` (not Canvas) | Validate via `web_fetch` \'97 confirm HTTP 200, no redirect to error page |\
| Mailto | `mailto:...` | Verify email address matches Course Configuration Block |\
\
**Execution steps:**\
\
1. **Extract all links** from the page HTML (every `<a href="...">` attribute)\
2. **Classify** each link by type using the table above\
3. **Validate** each link using the appropriate method\
4. **Fix** broken links:\
   - Internal Canvas links: correct the assignment ID, page slug, or discussion ID from the Course Map's Canvas IDs table\
   - External URLs: search for the current URL of the destination, or flag for instructor review if the resource has moved or been removed\
   - Anchors: correct the ID or remove the anchor link\
5. **Report** results in Build Notes: total links checked, any broken links found, fixes applied, and any links requiring instructor review\
\
**Rules:**\
- Never publish a page with unvalidated links\
- External links that return 3xx redirects: follow the redirect and update the `href` to the final destination URL\
- External links that return 4xx or 5xx: flag in Build Notes for instructor review \'97 do not silently remove\
- When the link-validator skill is available in the environment, use it instead of manual `web_fetch` validation\
- All external links must carry the `dp-external-link` class (see Global Hard Rules)\
\
---\
\
## QUALITY PRINCIPLES\
\
- **Quality over quantity** \'97 avoid arbitrary timing estimates or page-length requirements unless the instructor specifies them\
- **Progressive disclosure** \'97 show what matters now; hide what matters later\
- **Consistency** \'97 same patterns across all modules reduce cognitive load\
- **Accessibility first** \'97 every design decision must pass WCAG 2.1 AA\
- **No decoration** \'97 every UI element must serve a purpose documented in the Object Map\
- **Platform-agnostic framing** \'97 unless the platform itself is the pedagogical point, describe student work generically ("your prior process optimization project") so courses transfer across tools and terms\
- **Canvas is the system of record** \'97 when planning documents, memory, and Canvas state disagree, Canvas reflects reality. The Course Map reflects intent. Reconcile discrepancies explicitly.\
- **Dates belong in Canvas settings, not in HTML** \'97 use relative references ("due Sunday at 11:59 PM") in page content. Put specific calendar dates in Canvas assignment/discussion settings where they're machine-readable and update-safe.\
\
---\
\
## ANTI-PATTERNS (AVOID)\
\
| Anti-Pattern | Why It Fails | Do Instead |\
|---|---|---|\
| Tabs for sequential content | Students may skip tabs, missing steps | Use numbered list or accordion |\
| Tooltip for instructions | Screen readers may miss; mobile users can't hover | Put instructions inline |\
| Modal for critical info | Students may close without reading | Inline with visual emphasis |\
| Multiple accordions in sequence | Creates "click fatigue" | Use one accordion with multiple panels, or flatten content |\
| Decorative icons without meaning | Visual noise, accessibility burden | Use icons only with semantic purpose |\
| Raw URLs displayed | Inaccessible, ugly, error-prone | Always use descriptive linked text |\
| Hardcoded dates in HTML body | When schedule shifts, every page must be manually updated | Reference "Week N" or "due Sunday" patterns; put specific dates only in Canvas assignment settings |\
| Platform-specific language when unnecessary | Limits course reuse; alienates students on different tracks | Use platform-agnostic framing ("your prior process optimization project") unless the platform is the pedagogical point |\
| Updating pages without retrieving current HTML first | Canvas `update_page` is full replacement \'97 you lose everything you don't re-send | Always `get_page` \uc0\u8594  modify \u8594  `update_page` |\
| Trusting memory over Canvas state | Cross-session memory may reference deleted or renamed items | Verify current Canvas state before modifying any item |\
\
